var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"persistence/#Persistence","page":"Persistence","text":"By default sync_test_env creates a temporary environment in a system temp directory.  This is convenient for one-off runs but means Pkg must resolve packages from scratch every time, which can add a minute or more per run.","title":"Persistence"},{"category":"section","location":"persistence/#Why-persist?","page":"Persistence","text":"A persisted environment stores a complete manifest alongside the generated Project.toml. On Julia 1.11 and later, GpuTestEnv preserves the exact manifest filename Julia would prefer, including Manifest-v{major}.{minor}.toml when present. After the first successful sync it also records the source test project plus source-manifest snapshot, so unchanged persisted environments are reused directly instead of being re-created on every run. For a typical GPU test environment this cuts setup from ~60–90 seconds down to 1–2 seconds.\n\nPersistence is especially valuable in development workflows where you run julia --project=test test/runtests.jl repeatedly: after the first run you get near-instant startup on every subsequent run.","title":"Why persist?"},{"category":"section","location":"persistence/#Enabling-persistence","page":"Persistence","text":"Pass persist = true to place the environment at test/gpu_env/:\n\nGpuTestEnv.activate(; path = ROOT, persist = true)\n\nOverride the location with environment_path:\n\nGpuTestEnv.activate(; path = ROOT, environment_path = joinpath(ROOT, \"gpu_env\"))","title":"Enabling persistence"},{"category":"section","location":"persistence/#Git-ignore-warning","page":"Persistence","text":"When the persisted environment is inside a Git repository, GpuTestEnv checks whether the environment directory is gitignored and emits a warning when it is not:\n\n┌ Warning: The persisted GPU test environment is inside a Git repository but is not ignored.\n│   environment_path = \"/path/to/test/gpu_env\"\n│   recommendation = \"Add test/gpu_env/ to .gitignore …\"\n\nAdd the generated path to .gitignore to silence the warning:\n\ntest/gpu_env/\n\nDisable the check explicitly when needed:\n\nGpuTestEnv.activate(; path = ROOT, persist = true, warn_if_unignored = false)","title":"Git ignore warning"},{"category":"section","location":"persistence/#Refreshing-the-environment","page":"Persistence","text":"When your test dependencies change (e.g., you add a new package to test/Project.toml), the persisted environment needs to be rebuilt.  Delete the test/gpu_env/ directory and run the tests once to regenerate it:\n\nrm -rf test/gpu_env/\njulia --project=test test/runtests.jl","title":"Refreshing the environment"},{"category":"section","location":"persistence/#Behavior-across-Julia-versions","page":"Persistence","text":"Julia 1.11+: GpuTestEnv builds the synchronized GPU environment directly and reuses a matching Manifest-v{major}.{minor}.toml when available.\nJulia 1.10: activate bootstraps a compatible environment by stripping packages that require a newer Julia and developing path-sourced sub-packages explicitly. Persistence still works in this legacy mode, but the environment is rebuilt from the generated project instead of from a copied manifest.","title":"Behavior across Julia versions"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#API-Reference","page":"API","text":"","title":"API Reference"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Backend-types","page":"API","text":"","title":"Backend types"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Backend-metadata","page":"API","text":"","title":"Backend metadata"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Backend-queries-and-helpers","page":"API","text":"","title":"Backend queries and helpers"},{"category":"section","location":"api/#Environment-management","page":"API","text":"","title":"Environment management"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.BackendSpec","page":"API","text":"Metadata describing a supported GPU test backend.\n\nEach backend records its package name, UUID, module name, and primary array type.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.BackendSpec"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.GpuBackend","page":"API","text":"A resolved GPU test backend with its loaded module and primary array type.\n\nUse gpu_backends to obtain a list of GpuBackend instances for the current host. A GpuBackend is callable: backend(array) transfers array to the backend's device and returns the corresponding GPU array.\n\nThe name field holds the backend identifier. For JLArrays it is :JLArray (the array-type name); for native backends it is the module name (for example :CUDA). Use is_jlarray_backend to distinguish JLArrays from native backends.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.GpuBackend"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.is_jlarray_backend","page":"API","text":"is_jlarray_backend(backend::GpuBackend) -> Bool\n\nReturn whether backend is the JLArrays (CPU-side GPU mock) backend.\n\nArguments\n\nbackend::GpuBackend: the backend to check\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.is_jlarray_backend"},{"category":"type","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.SyncResult","page":"API","text":"A summary of a synchronized GPU test environment.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.SyncResult"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.supported_backends","page":"API","text":"supported_backends(; include_jlarrays=true)\n\nReturn the backend symbols supported by this package.\n\nArguments\n\ninclude_jlarrays::Bool=true: whether to include the JLArrays mock backend\n\nExamples\n\njulia> using GpuTestEnv\n\njulia> GpuTestEnv.supported_backends()\n(:JLArrays, :CUDA, :AMDGPU, :Metal, :oneAPI, :OpenCL)\n\njulia> GpuTestEnv.supported_backends(; include_jlarrays = false)\n(:CUDA, :AMDGPU, :Metal, :oneAPI, :OpenCL)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.supported_backends"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.backend_specs","page":"API","text":"backend_specs(; include_jlarrays=true)\n\nReturn metadata entries for supported backends.\n\nArguments\n\ninclude_jlarrays::Bool=true: whether to include metadata for the JLArrays backend\n\nExamples\n\njulia> using GpuTestEnv\n\njulia> [spec.name for spec in GpuTestEnv.backend_specs()]\n6-element Vector{Symbol}:\n :JLArrays\n :CUDA\n :AMDGPU\n :Metal\n :oneAPI\n :OpenCL\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.backend_specs"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.predict_backends","page":"API","text":"predict_backends(; include_jlarrays=true, probe=default_backend_probe,\n                 backends_to_test=collect(NATIVE_BACKENDS))\n\nPredict which GPU backends should be attempted on this host.\n\nprobe is a pure function that receives a backend symbol and returns true when the backend should be installed. The default probe uses direct host hints first and falls back to command-based checks without importing GPU packages.\n\nArguments\n\ninclude_jlarrays::Bool=true: whether to include JLArrays in the prediction\nprobe::Function=default_backend_probe: function to determine whether each backend should be tested\nbackends_to_test::AbstractVector{Symbol}: which native backends to probe (default: all supported native backends)\n\nExamples\n\njulia> using GpuTestEnv\n\njulia> GpuTestEnv.predict_backends(; include_jlarrays = false, probe = backend -> backend == :CUDA)\n1-element Vector{Symbol}:\n :CUDA\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.predict_backends"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.backend_modules_and_array_types","page":"API","text":"backend_modules_and_array_types(backends=collect(supported_backends());\n                                importer=default_backend_binding)\n\nReturn backend module and array-type pairs for backends.\n\nThe default behavior attempts to import each backend module and fetch its array type from that module. Backends that cannot be loaded are skipped.\n\nArguments\n\nbackends::AbstractVector{Symbol}: the backends to load (default: all supported backends)\nimporter::Function=default_backend_binding: function to load each backend module and extract its array type\n\nExamples\n\njulia> using GpuTestEnv\n\njulia> fake_loader = backend -> backend == :JLArrays ? (Main, Int) : nothing;\n\njulia> GpuTestEnv.backend_modules_and_array_types([:JLArrays, :CUDA]; importer = fake_loader)\n1-element Vector{Tuple{Module, DataType}}:\n (Main, Int64)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.backend_modules_and_array_types"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.resolve_backends","page":"API","text":"resolve_backends(backends; checker=default_backend_checker)\n\nFilter backends by runtime availability.\n\nchecker is a pure function that receives a backend symbol and returns true when the installed backend is usable.\n\nArguments\n\nbackends::AbstractVector{Symbol}: the backends to check for runtime availability\nchecker::Function=default_backend_checker: function to test each backend's runtime availability\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.resolve_backends"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.gpu_backends","page":"API","text":"gpu_backends(; include_jlarrays=true,\n               backends_to_test=collect(NATIVE_BACKENDS),\n               supports_fftw=false)\n\nReturn GpuBackend instances available on the current host.\n\nbackends_to_test restricts which native GPU backends are probed (default: all native backends supported by GpuTestEnv). Pass an explicit list such as [:CUDA, :AMDGPU] if you want to narrow the query set. Set supports_fftw = true to include only backends that support FFTW-based operators: JLArrays requires Julia 1.11+ for FFTW compatibility, and Metal / oneAPI / OpenCL are always excluded because they do not provide a FFTW-compatible FFT backend.\n\nArguments\n\ninclude_jlarrays::Bool=true: whether to include the JLArrays mock backend\nbackends_to_test::AbstractVector{Symbol}: which native backends to probe (default: all supported)\nsupports_fftw::Bool=false: if true, only return backends supporting FFTW-based operations\n\nExamples\n\njulia> using GpuTestEnv\n\njulia> backends = GpuTestEnv.gpu_backends(; backends_to_test = Symbol[]);\n\njulia> eltype(backends) <: GpuTestEnv.GpuBackend\ntrue\n\njulia> fftw_backends = GpuTestEnv.gpu_backends(; backends_to_test = Symbol[], supports_fftw = true);\n\njulia> typeof(fftw_backends) <: AbstractVector\ntrue\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.gpu_backends"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.gpu_zeros","page":"API","text":"gpu_zeros(backend::GpuBackend, T, dims...)\n\nReturn a zero-filled array on backend.\n\nBackends that do not expose their own zeros constructor fall back to creating the CPU array first and then transferring it with backend(array).\n\nArguments\n\nbackend::GpuBackend: the GPU backend to use\nT::Type: the element type for the array\ndims...: dimensions of the array\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.gpu_zeros"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.gpu_ones","page":"API","text":"gpu_ones(backend::GpuBackend, T, dims...)\n\nReturn a one-filled array on backend.\n\nArguments\n\nbackend::GpuBackend: the GPU backend to use\nT::Type: the element type for the array\ndims...: dimensions of the array\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.gpu_ones"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.gpu_randn","page":"API","text":"gpu_randn(backend::GpuBackend, dims...)\n\nReturn a GPU array of random normal values with Float64 elements.\n\nArguments\n\nbackend::GpuBackend: the GPU backend to use\ndims...: dimensions of the array\n\n\n\n\n\ngpu_randn(backend::GpuBackend, T, dims...)\n\nReturn a GPU array of random normal values with element type T.\n\nArguments\n\nbackend::GpuBackend: the GPU backend to use\nT::Type: the element type for the array\ndims...: dimensions of the array\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.gpu_randn"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.gpu_wrapper","page":"API","text":"gpu_wrapper(backend::GpuBackend, array)\n\nReturn the parametric wrapper type used by backend for array.\n\nThis is useful for APIs that expect a storage wrapper such as CuArray or JLArray rather than a concrete array type like CuArray{Float32, 2}.\n\nArguments\n\nbackend::GpuBackend: the GPU backend to query\narray: a representative array to determine the wrapper type from\n\nExamples\n\nusing GpuTestEnv\n\nbackends = gpu_backends()\nisempty(backends) && error(\"No functional backend found on this host\")\n\nbackend = first(backends)\nwrapper = gpu_wrapper(backend, Float32, 64, 64)\n\n\n\n\n\ngpu_wrapper(backend::GpuBackend, T, dims...)\n\nReturn the parametric wrapper type used by backend for T and dims.\n\nThis overload is convenient when you need to pass an array_type keyword to an API without first constructing a CPU array for transfer.\n\nArguments\n\nbackend::GpuBackend: the GPU backend to query\nT::Type: the element type\ndims...: dimensions that would be used\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.gpu_wrapper"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.sync_test_env","page":"API","text":"sync_test_env(pkg=nothing; path=nothing, include_jlarrays=true,\n              probe=default_backend_probe, checker=default_backend_checker,\n              backends_to_test=collect(NATIVE_BACKENDS), persist=false,\n              environment_path=nothing,\n              persisted_subdir=joinpath(\"test\", \"gpu_env\"),\n              warn_if_unignored=true, dry_run=false)\n\nCreate or update a GPU test environment.\n\nThe environment is copied from the package's test/Project.toml when present. The parent package is developed into the environment, backend packages are predicted and installed, and unusable backends are removed after their runtime checks fail.\n\npkg defaults to the active project's name. When path is provided, the package name is read from path/Project.toml if pkg is omitted.\n\nUnlike activate, this function restores the previously active Julia environment before returning. Use it when you want to inspect the synchronized environment or manage activation yourself.\n\nSet dry_run = true to inspect the planned backend list without installing packages.\n\nArguments\n\npkg::Union{Nothing, AbstractString}=nothing: package name (defaults to currently active project)\npath::Union{Nothing, AbstractString}=nothing: path to the package root directory\ninclude_jlarrays::Bool=true: whether to include the JLArrays mock backend\nprobe::Function=default_backend_probe: function to predict which backends to install\nchecker::Function=default_backend_checker: function to verify each backend's runtime availability\nbackends_to_test::AbstractVector{Symbol}: which native backends to attempt\npersist::Bool=false: whether to cache the environment in test/gpu_env/ for reuse\nenvironment_path::Union{Nothing, AbstractString}=nothing: custom path for the GPU test environment\npersisted_subdir::AbstractString=\"test/gpu_env\": subdirectory name when persisting\nwarn_if_unignored::Bool=true: whether to warn if persisted env is not in .gitignore\ndry_run::Bool=false: if true, return the plan without installing packages\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.sync_test_env"},{"category":"function","location":"api/#GpuTestEnv.activate","page":"API","text":"activate(pkg=nothing; path=nothing, include_jlarrays=true,\n         probe=default_backend_probe, checker=default_backend_checker,\n         backends_to_test=collect(NATIVE_BACKENDS), persist=false,\n         environment_path=nothing,\n         persisted_subdir=joinpath(\"test\", \"gpu_env\"),\n         warn_if_unignored=true, dry_run=false)\n\nCreate, synchronize, and activate a GPU test environment.\n\nOn Julia 1.11 and later this synchronizes the GPU environment and leaves that environment active for subsequent using statements. All keyword arguments are forwarded to sync_test_env, but unlike sync_test_env the new environment remains active on success.\n\nOn Julia 1.10 and earlier the full GPU environment cannot be built due to incomplete [sources] support. Instead this function bootstraps the calling package's test environment: it strips path-sourced dependencies and packages whose minimum required Julia version exceeds the running version, develops those paths explicitly, resolves and instantiates the environment, and pins JLArrays to 0.2.0 when include_jlarrays = true. Persistence-related keywords still apply in this legacy mode. In most downstream packages you can still call using GpuTestEnv directly; a separate bootstrap environment is only needed when the downstream test environment itself cannot resolve on Julia 1.10 before GpuTestEnv.activate(...) gets a chance to trim newer-only dependencies. Returns nothing on Julia < 1.11 when dry_run = false.\n\nArguments\n\npkg::Union{Nothing, AbstractString}=nothing: package name (defaults to currently active project)\npath::Union{Nothing, AbstractString}=nothing: path to the package root directory\ninclude_jlarrays::Bool=true: whether to include the JLArrays mock backend\nprobe::Function=default_backend_probe: function to predict which backends to install\nchecker::Function=default_backend_checker: function to verify each backend's runtime availability\nbackends_to_test::AbstractVector{Symbol}: which native backends to attempt\npersist::Bool=false: whether to cache the environment in test/gpu_env/ for reuse\nenvironment_path::Union{Nothing, AbstractString}=nothing: custom path for the GPU test environment\npersisted_subdir::AbstractString=\"test/gpu_env\": subdirectory name when persisting\nwarn_if_unignored::Bool=true: whether to warn if persisted env is not in .gitignore\ndry_run::Bool=false: if true, return the plan without installing packages\n\nExample\n\n# In test/runtests.jl (or equivalent bootstrapper):\nusing GpuTestEnv\nconst ROOT = normpath(joinpath(@__DIR__, \"..\"))\nGpuTestEnv.activate(; path = ROOT, persist = true)\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"GpuTestEnv.activate"},{"category":"section","location":"#GpuTestEnv","page":"Home","text":"GpuTestEnv helps downstream packages create a GPU-aware test environment without hard-coding every GPU backend into their main test dependencies.\n\nThe core workflow:\n\nCopy or create a temporary test environment from test/Project.toml.\nDevelop the parent package into that environment.\nPredict which GPU backends are worth attempting on the current host.\nInstall those backends.\nRun each backend's runtime-availability check and keep only the usable ones.\n\nBoth modern test environments based on test/Project.toml and legacy test-only dependencies defined with [extras] and [targets] in the root project are supported.","title":"GpuTestEnv"},{"category":"section","location":"#Supported-backends","page":"Home","text":"Symbol Package Array type\n:JLArrays JLArrays JLArray\n:CUDA CUDA CuArray\n:AMDGPU AMDGPU ROCArray\n:Metal Metal MtlArray\n:oneAPI oneAPI oneArray\n:OpenCL OpenCL CLArray\n\nBackend prediction prefers direct host hints such as Linux device nodes and PCI vendor IDs, Windows video-controller names, and macOS display metadata. Command-line tools like nvidia-smi, rocminfo, sycl-ls, and clinfo remain fallback probes.","title":"Supported backends"},{"category":"section","location":"#Test-environment-example","page":"Home","text":"# test/runtests.jl\nusing GpuTestEnv\n\nconst ROOT = normpath(joinpath(@__DIR__, \"..\"))\nGpuTestEnv.activate(; path = ROOT, persist = true)\n\nOn Julia 1.10, a separate bootstrap environment is only needed if the downstream test environment cannot be resolved before GpuTestEnv.activate(...) gets a chance to remove newer-only dependencies.","title":"Test environment example"},{"category":"section","location":"#Benchmarking-environment-example","page":"Home","text":"Run the script as julia --project=benchmark benchmark/gpu_benchmark.jl.\n\n# benchmark/gpu_benchmark.jl\nusing GpuTestEnv\n\nconst ROOT = normpath(joinpath(@__DIR__, \"..\"))\nGpuTestEnv.activate(\"MyPackage\"; path = ROOT, persist = false, include_jlarrays = false)\n\nusing MyPackage, BenchmarkTools\n\n# Use the first available GPU backend\nbackend = first(gpu_backends(; include_jlarrays = false))\nx_gpu = backend(randn(Float32, 1024))\n\nNo need to add CUDA or other GPU packages to the benchmark Project.toml; GpuTestEnv detects and installs them during activate. While GpuTestEnv is not yet registered, keep a [sources] path entry for it in the benchmark project.","title":"Benchmarking environment example"},{"category":"section","location":"#Working-with-backends-after-activation","page":"Home","text":"julia> using GpuTestEnv\n\njulia> fake_loader = backend -> backend == :JLArrays ? (Main, Int) : nothing;\n\njulia> GpuTestEnv.backend_modules_and_array_types([:JLArrays, :CUDA]; importer = fake_loader)\n1-element Vector{Tuple{Module, DataType}}:\n (Main, Int64)\n\nQuery the available backends after activate has run:\n\nbackends = gpu_backends()                          # JLArrays + all native backends that resolve here\nbackends_fftw = gpu_backends(; supports_fftw = true)  # only FFTW-compatible\nall_tested = gpu_backends(\n    ;\n    include_jlarrays = false,\n    backends_to_test = collect(supported_backends(; include_jlarrays = false)),\n)\n\nfor backend in backends\n    x = gpu_randn(backend, Float32, 128, 128)\n    @show backend.name, typeof(x)\nend\n\nbackends_to_test only narrows the backend probe/query set. Use it when you want to skip known-irrelevant backends or limit the default all-native query set to a smaller subset such as CUDA and AMDGPU.","title":"Working with backends after activation"},{"category":"section","location":"#sync*test*env-versus-activate","page":"Home","text":"Use sync_test_env when you want a SyncResult describing the GPU environment but you do not want to leave that environment active. Use activate when the synchronized GPU environment should stay active for the rest of the current Julia session.","title":"synctestenv versus activate"},{"category":"section","location":"#JLArrays-opt-out","page":"Home","text":"JLArrays is enabled by default.  Skip it when testing native GPU paths only:\n\nGpuTestEnv.activate(; path = ROOT, include_jlarrays = false)","title":"JLArrays opt-out"},{"category":"section","location":"#Persistent-environments","page":"Home","text":"See Persistence for details on why persisting the environment speeds up repeated test runs and how to configure it.","title":"Persistent environments"}]
}
